3 COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
FOR ENGROSSED
4 HOUSE BILL NO. 4305 By: Blair of the House
5 and
6 Frix of the Senate
7
8
9 An Act relating to ad valorem tax; defining terms;
providing for application of act; prescribing
10 valuation method for determining fair cash value of
certain property; requiring the county assessor to
11 determine certain process; requiring certain
organizations to deliver certain audit by certain
12 date; authorizing assessor to extend deadline;
amending 68 O.S. 2021, Section 2887, as amended by
13 Section 1, Chapter 260, O.S.L. 2023 (68 O.S. Supp.
2025, Section 2887), which relates to property exempt
14 from ad valorem taxation; prohibiting certain clause
to be construed to prohibit certain compensation;
15 updating statutory language; updating statutory
references; providing for codification; and providing
16 an effective date.
17
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2865.1 of Title 68, unless there
22 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 A. As used in this act:
24
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB4305 SFLR Page 1
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 1. “Active construction” means any property that is being
2 constructed or renovated that has yet to place in service all of its
3 buildings;
4 2. “Audit” means an audit of the financial operations of the
5 property provided by a third-party certified public accountant or
6 financial statements certified by the organization to be true and
7 accurate;
8 3. “Lease-up” means any property that has an actual occupancy
9 of less than ninety percent (90%), that is under or has been under
10 active construction, and is in the process of leasing units;
11 4. “Net operating income” means gross restricted rent income
12 from the property minus operating expenses and replacement reserve
13 deposits, before debt service, depreciation, amortization, capital
14 expenditures, and income taxes;
15 5. “Organization” means a property owner meeting the
16 requirements under subsection B of this section; and
17 6. “Restricted rent” means the actual rental rates that are
18 restricted by the programs described in subsection B of this
19 section.
20 B. This act shall only apply to real property owned by an
21 organization:
22 1. For the purpose of renting the property to a low-income or
23 moderate-income individual or family who satisfies the income
24 eligibility requirements of the organization;
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB4305 SFLR Page 2
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 2. That was financed in whole or in part through allocation of
2 the federal low-income housing tax credit authorized pursuant to 26
3 U.S.C., Section 42, and is subject to a land use agreement or
4 regulatory agreement that has not expired or been terminated;
5 3. That does not receive exempt treatment under Section 2887 of
6 Title 68 of the Oklahoma Statutes; and
7 4. The owner of which has not entered into any agreement with
8 any taxing unit to make payments to the taxing unit instead of taxes
9 on the property.
10 C. In determining the fair cash value of a property described
11 in subsection B of this section, the county assessor shall determine
12 the fair cash value of property that is under active construction or
13 lease-up on January 1 of the current tax year in the manner provided
14 by Section 8 of Article X of the Oklahoma Constitution using the
15 restricted rent income approach method, provided that the county
16 assessor shall estimate the net operating income of the property
17 based on the projected restricted rent income and expenses of the
18 organization for the first full year of operation, as adjusted to
19 reflect the average occupancy during the lease-up period.
20 D. In determining the fair cash value for a property for any
21 subsequent tax year, the county assessor shall determine the fair
22 cash value of the property based upon the restricted rent income
23 approach method utilizing the net operating income of the property
24 from the audit provided by the organization.
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB4305 SFLR Page 3
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 E. In determining the fair cash value of property described in
2 subsection B of this section, the county assessor shall not consider
3 the value or any amount of any federal or state low-income housing
4 tax credits as a component of the fair cash value or income
5 attributable to the property.
6 F. The county assessor shall determine a formal process for
7 determining market-derived capitalization rates to be applied to the
8 net operating income of the property based on project and investor
9 data for comparable properties with restricted rents.
10 G. Not later than May 1 of each year, the organization shall
11 deliver to the county assessor the audit for the preceding year.
12 The county assessor may extend the deadline for good cause shown.
13 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 68 O.S. 2021, Section 2887, as
14 amended by Section 1, Chapter 260, O.S.L. 2023 (68 O.S. Supp. 2025,
15 Section 2887), is amended to read as follows:
16 Section 2887. The following property shall be exempt from ad
17 valorem taxation:
18 1. All property of the United States, and such property as may
19 be exempt by reason of treaty stipulations existing at statehood
20 between the Indians and the United States government, or by reason
21 of federal laws in effect at statehood, during the time such
22 treaties or federal laws are in force and effect. In instances
23 where a federal agency has obtained title to property through
24 foreclosure, voluntary or involuntary liquidation or bankruptcy,
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB4305 SFLR Page 4
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 whic h was previously subject to ad valorem taxation, the property
2 may continue to be assessed for ad valorem taxes if such federal
3 agency has agreed to pay such taxes;
4 2. All property of this state, and of the counties, school
5 districts, and municipalities of this state, including property
6 acquired for the use of such entities pursuant to the terms of a
7 lease-purchase agreement which provides for the passage of title or
8 the release of security interest, if applicable, upon payment of all
9 rental payments and an additional nominal amount;
10 3. All property of any college or school, provided such
11 property is devoted exclusively and directly to the appropriate
12 objects of such college or school within this state and all property
13 used exclusively for nonprofit schools and colleges;
14 4. The books, papers, furniture and scientific or other
15 apparatus pertaining to any institution, college or society referred
16 to in paragraph 3 of this section, and devoted exclusively and
17 directly for the purpose above contemplated, and the like property
18 of students in any such institution or college, while such property
19 is used for the purpose of their education;
20 5. All fraternal orphan homes and other orphan homes;
21 6. All property used for free public libraries, free museums,
22 public cemeteries, or free public schools;
23 7. All property used exclusively and directly for fraternal or
24 religious purposes within this state. For purposes of this
SENATE FLOOR VERSION - HB4305 SFLR Page 5
(Bold face denotes Committee Amendments)

1 para graph, an exemption based on religious purposes includes real
2 property owned by a church which allows its premises to be used by
3 an entity if such entity is not required to make rental payments to
4 the church, is not required to execute a formal lease agreement with
5 respect to its occupancy of the church premises and conducts
6 instruction of children from any or all grades for ages preschool
7 through twelfth grade, including religious instruction consistent
8 with the doctrines of the church the premises of which are being
9 used for that purpose. For purposes of this paragraph, a
10 requirement by a church to be reimbursed by the entity for utility
11 expenses, janitorial services or similar expenses shall not be a
12 basis upon which to remove or deny the exempt status of church
13 property. Exempt status of church property shall not be removed nor
14 shall church property be allocated between taxable and exempt status
15 based on the use of church premises by an entity as described by
16 this paragraph.
17 For purposes of administering the exemption authorized by this
18 section and in order to determine whether a single family
19 residential property is used exclusively and directly for fraternal
20 or religious purposes, the fair cash value of a single family
21 residential property, for which an exemption is claimed as
22 authorized by this subsection section, in excess of Five Hundred
23 Thousand Dollars ($500,000.00) for the applicable assessment year
24 shall not be exempt from taxation;
